To save text to a local file in a JavaScript web app, you can use the Blob and anchor tag combination. Here's an example of how this can be done:

```javascript
// Create a new Blob object containing your text
var blob = new Blob(["Your text goes here"], {type: "text/plain;charset=utf-8"});

// Create a unique URL for the Blob object
var url = window.URL.createObjectURL(blob);

// Create a download link and set its href attribute to the URL of the Blob object
var downloadLink = document.createElement("a");
downloadLink.href = url;

// Set the visibility of the download link to hidden so it's not visible in the page
downloadLink.style.visibility = "hidden";

// Add a download attribute to the download link, specifying the file name you want for the saved file
downloadLink.setAttribute("download", "YourFileName.txt");

// Append the download link to the body of the document
document.body.appendChild(downloadLink);

// Click the download link programmatically to initiate the download
downloadLink.click();

// Remove the download link from the body of the document
document.body.removeChild(downloadLink);
```

Replace "Your text goes here" with your actual text and "YourFileName.txt" with the desired file name for the saved file. When this code is executed in a JavaScript web app, it will prompt the user to save your text as a local file named YourFileName.txt.
